chunks.chunk: In the second quarter of fiscal year 2025, Broadcom, Inc. reported total revenue of $15 billion, marking a 20% increase year-on-year, driven entirely by organic growth. This growth was particularly fueled by the strength in AI semiconductors, which saw a revenue increase of 46% year-on-year, contributing over $4.4 billion. The company's semiconductor revenue reached $8.4 billion, with a notable acceleration from 11% growth in Q1 to 17% in Q2. The momentum in AI networking, which grew over 170% year-on-year, was also highlighted, representing 40% of the AI revenue, showcasing the importance of Ethernet as a preferred protocol among hyperscale customers.

The introduction of the Tomahawk 6 switch, capable of 102.4 terabits per second, is set to enhance performance in AI clusters by enabling the deployment of over 100,000 AI accelerators in just two tiers, reducing latency and power consumption. Broadcom's focus on custom AI accelerators is evident, with expectations for at least three customers to deploy 1 million AI accelerated clusters by 2027. The company anticipates a significant percentage of these deployments to be custom XPUs, indicating a strong commitment from partners to invest despite economic uncertainties. This trend is expected to sustain Broadcom's growth rate into fiscal 2026.

Looking ahead to Q3, Broadcom forecasts AI semiconductor revenue to reach $5.1 billion, reflecting a 60% increase year-on-year, marking the 10th consecutive quarter of growth. In contrast, non-AI semiconductor revenue is projected to remain around $4 billion, down 5% year-on-year, with expectations of sequential growth in enterprise networking and broadband segments. The infrastructure software segment also showed robust growth, with revenue of $6.6 billion, up 25% year-on-year, driven by the transition of enterprise customers to the VCF software stack subscription model. This shift is expected to continue, with Q3 infrastructure software revenue projected at approximately $6.7 billion, up 16% year-on-year.

Broadcom's consolidated gross margin for Q2 was reported at 79.4%, exceeding initial guidance, while operating income rose to $9.8 billion, up 37% year-on-year. The semiconductor solution segment's gross margin improved to approximately 69%, driven by a favorable product mix, while infrastructure software gross margin reached 93%. The company remains focused on maintaining a disciplined approach to capital allocation, with plans to prioritize debt reduction while also returning capital to shareholders through dividends and stock repurchases. In Q2, Broadcom paid $2.8 billion in cash dividends and repurchased approximately 25 million shares, indicating a strong commitment to shareholder returns.

During the Q&A session, discussions centered around the growth trajectory of AI revenue and the impact of XPUs on the overall business. Broadcom's management expressed confidence in sustaining a 60% year-on-year growth rate into fiscal 2026, driven by increased demand for AI accelerators and networking solutions. The interplay between training and inference workloads was highlighted, with management noting that the need to monetize inference is driving demand among hyperscale customers. Additionally, the conversation touched on the competitive landscape of networking protocols, with Broadcom emphasizing the advantages of Ethernet as an open standard for scale-up and scale-out networking, positioning the company favorably in the evolving market.
